# Molly Fish: The Euryhaline Livebearer

Molly Fish stand apart from most freshwater aquarium fish in one remarkable way: they are genuinely euryhaline — capable of living in fresh water, brackish water, and full seawater. Wild populations have been documented in coastal estuaries, marine lagoons, freshwater rivers, and everything in between. This biological flexibility has made them hardy aquarium fish, but it also means that the "standard freshwater" conditions most aquarists apply are actually suboptimal. Mollies thrive with some mineral content, harder water, and benefit from occasional salt supplementation in ways that truly freshwater species never would.

---

## Species and Natural Habitat

Three main species contribute to the hobby's "Molly":

**Poecilia sphenops** (Short-fin Molly) — The foundational aquarium Molly. Small, torpedo-shaped, 6–8 cm. Found from Mexico through Central America in freshwater and brackish coastal habitats. The ancestor of most Black Molly, Dalmatian, and Balloon Molly varieties.

**Poecilia latipinna** (Sailfin Molly) — Larger, 10–12 cm, with a spectacular enlarged dorsal fin in males that can exceed body height. Native to the US Gulf Coast states and Florida. Requires more space than *P. sphenops*.

**Poecilia velifera** (Yucatan Molly) — Largest of the three; found in Yucatan Peninsula coastal waters. Less common in the hobby but spectacular in breeding condition males.

All inhabit warm, alkaline, often brackish water. The Gulf Coast populations of *P. latipinna* regularly inhabit coastal marshes and estuaries with significant salinity.

---

## The Euryhaline Advantage

Molly Fish possess an unusual osmoregulatory flexibility. While most freshwater fish die rapidly in saltwater (due to osmotic shock), Mollies can gradually acclimate to salinities up to full seawater (35 ppt). In the aquarium hobby this manifests as:

**Disease resistance in brackish setups:** Many freshwater pathogens (Ich, some bacterial infections) cannot survive in saline environments. Mollies kept in light brackish water (2–5 ppt) often show dramatically reduced disease frequency compared to the same fish in freshwater.

**Improved fin condition:** Fin rot and fraying are significantly less common in moderately saline setups.

**Natural behaviour:** Brackish conditions more closely replicate wild coastal habitat in Gulf Coast populations.

**Practical brackish setup:** 1 tablespoon of aquarium salt or marine salt (sea salt, not table salt) per 10 litres. This equates to roughly 2–3 ppt salinity — comfortable for Mollies, tolerated by most hardy freshwater companions, but not suitable for true soft-water species (Tetras, Discus, Corydoras).

---

## Water Parameters

**Temperature:** 24–28°C. Optimal 26–27°C. Below 22°C immune function weakens significantly.

**pH:** 7.0–8.5. Hard alkaline water is strongly preferred. Mollies in soft, acidic water (below pH 7.0) show reduced health and breeding activity.

**Hardness:** 12–30 dGH. One of the hardest-water freshwater fish in the hobby. Tap water is usually fine; hard water areas benefit Mollies.

**Salinity (optional but beneficial):** 2–5 ppt brackish improves health. Not mandatory but strongly recommended for breeding setups and disease-prone individuals.

