## Breeding — The Livebearer Advantage

Mollies are livebearers — the female retains fertilised eggs internally and gives birth to free-swimming, fully formed fry. There are no eggs to guard, no larval stage, and fry emerge as miniature adults capable of immediate independent feeding.

### Gestation

28–35 days depending on temperature. Warmer temperatures shorten gestation.

### Birth

A gravid female's abdomen becomes noticeably rounded and develops a dark "gravid spot" near the vent (more visible in light-coloured varieties). As birth approaches, the female may become less active and seek cover. Births occur over several hours; a single female can produce 10–100+ fry per birth depending on size, age, and condition.

### Fry Survival

**Adults eat fry.** Without cover or separation, most fry will be consumed within hours of birth.

**Options:**
1. **Dense planting** — Fry hide in plants immediately after birth; survival is partial but easier
2. **Breeding trap** (used cautiously) — Small net or plastic container inside the main tank. Limits stress on the female but confinement during birth causes some welfare concerns
3. **Separate fry tank** — Best option; move gravid female to a separate tank 1–2 days before expected birth, then return her after birth

### Fry Foods

Fry are large enough at birth to accept:
- Finely crushed adult flakes
- **Baby Brine Shrimp nauplii** — Ideal first food. **[Live BBS from Blackwater Aquatics](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/collections/live-foods).**
- **Microworms** — Excellent size match. **[Available at Blackwater Aquatics](https://blackwateraquatics.ca/collections/live-foods).**
- Powdered spirulina

### Sperm Storage

Female Mollies (and all poecilid livebearers) can store sperm after a single mating for up to 6 months. A female purchased from a mixed-sex tank may produce multiple broods without a male present. This surprises many new keepers.

